				\begin{document}$$Cs=\frac{I{\rm{\Delta }}t}{m3.6}$$\end{document}where Cs is the specific capacity (mA h g−1); I is the current (A); Δt is the discharging time (s), and m is the mass of active material (g).). The calculated specific capacity was 824 C g−1 (229 mA h g−1), 415 C g−1 (115 mA h g−1), 197 C g−1 (55 mA h g−1), 58 C g−1 (16 mA h g−1), and 36 C g−1 (10 mA h g−1) at a specific applied current of 2.5, 5, 7.5, 10, and 12.5 A g−1, respectively. The Ag/NiO honeycomb nanoarrays delivered a maximum specific capacity of 824 C g−1 at a specific current of 2.5 A g−1.Figure 7
